postcontent: You think some of the Colt Snakes are rare? No where near as rare as this beauty!! (But yes, you have to be a 1911 platform fan) Here is a 1 year production (1999) XS Model Colt C.C.O. Not to be confused with the first year run (1998) where all the frames were painted black. And definitely not to be confused with todays much cheaper built C.C.O series. Do your research, there were very few of these models made, and if you google search this model the few that you will find all have the same LF111xx serial number prefix. Im not saying this is a 100 gun production run, but the only others that I have seen all have the same LF111xx serial number starting the 5 digit serial number. Thelast one known to sell was sold on Gunbroker back in 2010 and sold for $3400.00 And that was 6 years ago. Maybe the market was up? Just using that as a referance. But offering $800-$1500 guns as trade will not even be in the ballpark for this gun.  I purchased this gun from the ORIGINAL owner who bought it back in 1999. It has NEVER had a round instered in the mag nor has it ever had one chambered. This gun has been white glove handled only and very few times in its 18 year life so far. This is one of my most prized possessions and the only reason it and a few others are being sold is that I have found my true dream gun (A transferable Auto Ordinance Thompson Machine Gun, yes, the full auto Al Capones favorite gun. So, maybe with a new administration in Washington DC I’ll be able to buy a firearm without having to sell another one first. But for now, that’s all my budget will allow. I have my eye on a SCCY CX-1 or a Ruger LC9. In order to swing that, I need to sell something I already have. Here it is.
Walther PK380. Less than 500 rounds have been sent downrange (always cleaned and oiled). The handgun comes with three OEM 8 round magazines with finger rests, an OEM Walther laser (easily removed), original plastic hard case, and take-down tool.
The handgun itself: 380acp. Conceal carry design. Features low profile three-dot polymer combat sights, Tenifer coated slide and barrel, loaded chamber viewport, rear slide serrations and ambidextrous manual safety. Ergonomic Walther grip, paddle-style ambidextrous magazine release levers, ambidextrous slide stop. Picatinny accessory rail. Double/single action trigger. 11 pound pull for double action; 4 pound pull for single action. Eight round magazine with finger rest. It is small and good looking. That makes the PK380 excellent for concealed carry. Its small grip is ideal for shooters with small hands although it fits perfectly in my big paws. The slide is easy to operate, making it a good choice for women or guys tired of breaking a sweat every time they have to rack the slide. At 18oz it’s easy to carry and conceal.
$385 firm. Must have valid Wisconsin DL and a Wisconsin CCW, no exceptions. Located in Waterford (western Racine Co.).

title: For Sale:  Historically Significant Gold Medal Winning Olympic Target Rifle 1900 Paris Olympics
postcontent: For sale I have an incredible Martini Rifle that was once owned by the greatest Swiss Target shooter and many beleive the greatest target shooter ever to walk the planet one Konrad Staheli. This Rifle was purchased along with several others from a museum in France that was closing their doors. This Rifle is believed to be the same one that Konrad Staheli used to win the Gold Medal at the 1900 Olympic Games in Paris France on the 300 meter kneeling Rifle as well as many of his other 117 Medals and 24 World Chamionship Titles. The extensive research that I have done points to this being the exact rifle including information given to me by the museum where this Rifle has been on display for the last 60 years. This is an incredible opportunity to own one of the only Olympic Gold Medal Winning Rifles known in private hands today as the large majority of them are in museums. In the pictures below I am including a picture of Konrad Staheli holding this Rifle proving this is indeed the one that won Olympic Gold. This was displayed in the museum as the Rifle that won Olympic Gold in the 1900 Paris Olympics as well as the World Championship in all three Target positions at Lyons in 1904, Zurich in 1907, Hamburg in 1909, Rome in 1911, Biarritz in 1912, and camp perry in 1913. I have spoken with two very large auction companies who would love to have this Rifle for one of their upcoming auctions but given the very steep consigning fees I wanted to try and sell it here first and if it doesn't sell it will go to one of these auction houses. The price I am listing this at is below the estimate given to me by either auction house proving the rarity of this Rifle. Keep in mind that this Rifle not only won a gold medal in the olympics but was owned by probably the greatest target shooter of all time. Now to the Rifle itself. The Rifle is in incredible condition for its age and the bore is immaculate and would rate a 9 out of 10. It features fully adjustable front and rear sights ( windage and elevation) with the rear sight having many different adjustments and the front sight has the option of interchangeable blades. The Rifle is very heavy and tips the scales at 12.2 lbs. The barrel is very heavy and has flutes running nearly the full length of the barrel. It also features double set triggers and a target stock with a raised cheekpiece and Swiss Target buttplate that cups your shoulder incredibly well. The Rifle is chambered in .41 Swiss and I will be including the cartridge shown for display with the Rifle. The case coloring is still visable on both sides of the receiver, lever, and breechblock. The Schutzen Museum in Switzerland has a whole wing dedicated to Konrad Staheli including a gun nearly identical to this one being held by a life size figure of konrad but that one isn't the one that won the Gold Medal in the olympics since it has a palm rest/ lever attached to the underside of the forearm which weren't allowed to be used in the kneeling portion of the olympic contest for which his gold medal was one. This information along with the picture I have provided with him posing with this exact gun has me nearly 100% convinced this is the Olympic gun as it does not feature a palm rest lever. The only drawback I can find is that the wood forend has a small very tight crack that could be repaired quite easily. The barrel finish is a mix of original brown as this gun was originally browned not blued and silver/Grey as its starting to loose its finish in places but it is an overall very pleasing patina color. If his gun can be 100% positively identified as the Gold Medal Winning 1900 Olympic Rifle of Konrad Staheli such as through serial number which I believe can be found through Olympic records with more research you are looking at a $20,000 plus Rifle if sent to auction. Even if it's not the Gold Medal Winning rifle it was still owned and used to win many championships by arguably the greatest target shooter who ever lived. With that said serious inquiries only. Many pictures are available to send. Email, call or text REDACTED
